# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: homological-algebra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] In mathematics, an **abelian category** is a category in which morphisms and objects can be added and in which kernels and cokernels exist and have desirable properties.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] The motivating prototypical example of an abelian category is the category of abelian groups, **Ab**.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Abelian categories are very *stable* categories; for example they are regular and they satisfy the snake lemma.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] The class of abelian categories is closed under several categorical constructions, for example, the category of chain complexes of an abelian category, or the category of functors from a small category to an abelian category are abelian as well.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] These stability properties make them inevitable in homological algebra and beyond; the theory has major applications in algebraic geometry, cohomology and pure category theory.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Mac Lane says Alexander Grothendieck defined abelian categories in 1957, but there is a reference that says Eilenberg's disciple, Buchsbaum, had proposed the concept in his 1955 PhD thesis, and Grothendieck popularized it under the name "abelian category".
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Note that the enriched structure on hom-sets is a *consequence* of the first three axioms of the first definition.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] This highlights the foundational relevance of the category of Abelian groups in the theory and its canonical nature.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] The concept of exact sequence arises naturally in this setting, and it turns out that exact functors, i.e. the functors preserving exact sequences in various senses, are the relevant functors between abelian categories.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] This *exactness* concept has been axiomatized in the theory of exact categories, forming a very special case of regular categories.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] In his Tōhoku article, Grothendieck listed four additional axioms (and their duals) that an abelian category **A** might satisfy.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] These axioms are still in common use to this day.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] They are what make an additive category abelian.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Grothendieck also gave axioms AB6) and AB6*).
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Given any pair *A*, *B* of objects in an abelian category, there is a special zero morphism from *A* to *B*.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] This can be defined as the zero element of the hom-set Hom(*A*,*B*), since this is an abelian group.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Alternatively, it can be defined as the unique composition *A* → 0 → *B*, where 0 is the zero object of the abelian category.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] In an abelian category, every morphism *f* can be written as the composition of an epimorphism followed by a monomorphism.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] This epimorphism is called the *coimage* of *f*, while the monomorphism is called the *image* of *f*.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Subobjects and quotient objects are well-behaved in abelian categories.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] For example, the poset of subobjects of any given object *A* is a bounded lattice.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Every abelian category **A** is a module over the monoidal category of finitely generated abelian groups; that is, we can form a tensor product of a finitely generated abelian group *G* and any object *A* of **A**.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] The abelian category is also a comodule; Hom(*G*,*A*) can be interpreted as an object of **A**.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] If **A** is complete, then we can remove the requirement that *G* be finitely generated; most generally, we can form finitary enriched limits in **A**.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Given an object A in an abelian category, **flatness** refers to the idea that $-\otimes A$ is an exact functor.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] See flat module or, for more generality, flat morphism.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Abelian categories are the most general setting for homological algebra.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] All of the constructions used in that field are relevant, such as exact sequences, and especially short exact sequences, and derived functors.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Important theorems that apply in all abelian categories include the five lemma (and the short five lemma as a special case), as well as the snake lemma (and the nine lemma as a special case).
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] This technical condition is rather strong and excludes many natural examples of abelian categories found in nature.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] For example, most module categories over a ring R are not semi-simple; in fact, this is the case if and only if R is a semisimple ring.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] There do exist some natural counter-examples of abelian categories which are not semi-simple, such as certain categories of representations.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] which only has one subrepresentation of dimension 1 .
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] In fact, this is true for any unipotent grouppg 112.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] There are numerous types of (full, additive) subcategories of abelian categories that occur in nature, as well as some conflicting terminology.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Let **A** be an abelian category, **C** a full, additive subcategory, and *I* the inclusion functor.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Here is an explicit example of a full, additive subcategory of an abelian category that is itself abelian but the inclusion functor is not exact.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Let *k* be a field, $T_{n}$ the algebra of upper-triangular $n\times n$ matrices over *k*, and $\mathbf {A} _{n}$ the category of finite-dimensional $T_{n}$ -modules.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Then each $\mathbf {A} _{n}$ is an abelian category and we have an inclusion functor $I\colon \mathbf {A} _{2}\to \mathbf {A} _{3}$ identifying the simple projective, simple injective and indecomposable projective-injective modules.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] The essential image of *I* is a full, additive subcategory, but *I* is not exact.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Abelian categories were introduced by Buchsbaum (1955) (under the name of "exact category") and Grothendieck (1957) in order to unify various cohomology theories.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] At the time, there was a cohomology theory for sheaves, and a cohomology theory for groups.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] The two were defined differently, but they had similar properties.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] In fact, much of category theory was developed as a language to study these similarities.
[src:homological-algebra/abelian-category] Grothendieck unified the two theories: they both arise as derived functors on abelian categories; the abelian category of sheaves of abelian groups on a topological space, and the abelian category of *G*-modules for a given group *G*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] In mathematics, a **chain complex** is an algebraic structure that consists of a sequence of abelian groups (or modules) and a sequence of homomorphisms between consecutive groups such that the image of each homomorphism is contained in the kernel of the next.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Associated to a chain complex is its homology, which is (loosely speaking) a measure of the failure of a chain complex to be exact.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] A **cochain complex** is similar to a chain complex, except that its homomorphisms are in the opposite direction.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The homology of a cochain complex is called its cohomology.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] In algebraic topology, the singular chain complex of a topological space X is constructed using continuous maps from a simplex to X, and the homomorphisms of the chain complex capture how these maps restrict to the boundary of the simplex.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The homology of this chain complex is called the singular homology of X, and is a commonly used invariant of a topological space.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Chain complexes are studied in homological algebra, but are used in several areas of mathematics, including abstract algebra, Galois theory, differential geometry and algebraic geometry.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] They can be defined more generally in abelian categories.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Explicitly, the differentials satisfy $d_{n}\circ d_{n+1}=0$ for all n , or, concisely, $d^{2}=0$ .
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The **cochain complex** $(A^{\bullet },d^{\bullet })$ is the dual notion to a chain complex.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] It consists of a sequence of abelian groups or modules $\cdots ,A^{0},A^{1},A^{2},\dots$ connected by homomorphisms (**coboundary operators**) $d^{n}:A^{n}\to A^{n+1}$ satisfying $d^{n+1}\circ d^{n}=0$ .
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] In both cases, the index n is referred to as the **degree** (or **dimension**).
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The difference between chain and cochain complexes is that, in chain complexes, the differentials decrease dimension, whereas in cochain complexes they increase dimension.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] All the concepts and definitions for chain complexes apply to cochain complexes, except that they will follow this different convention for dimension, and often terms will be given the prefix *co-*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] In this article, definitions will be given for chain complexes when the distinction is not required.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] A **bounded chain complex** is one in which almost all the $A_{n}$ are 0; that is, a finite complex extended to the left and right by 0.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] An example is the chain complex defining the simplicial homology of a finite simplicial complex.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] A chain complex is **bounded above** if all modules above some fixed degree N are 0, and is **bounded below** if all modules below some fixed degree are 0.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Clearly, a complex is bounded both above and below if and only if the complex is bounded.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The elements of the individual groups of a (co)chain complex are called **(co)chains**.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The elements in the kernel of d are called **(co)cycles** (or **closed** elements), and the elements in the image of *d* are called **(co)boundaries** (or **exact** elements).
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Right from the definition of the differential, all boundaries are cycles.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] An **exact sequence** (or **exact** complex) is a chain complex whose homology groups are all zero.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] This means all closed elements in the complex are exact.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] A **short exact sequence** is a bounded exact sequence in which only the groups *A**k*, *A**k*+1, *A**k*+2 may be nonzero.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] For example, the following chain complex is a short exact sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] In the middle group, the closed elements are the elements p**Z**; these are clearly the exact elements in this group.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] This is written out in the following commutative diagram.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] A chain map sends cycles to cycles and boundaries to boundaries, and thus induces a map on homology $(f_{\bullet })_{*}:H_{\bullet }(A_{\bullet },d_{A,\bullet })\rightarrow H_{\bullet }(B_{\bullet },d_{B,\bullet })$ .
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] A continuous map *f* between topological spaces *X* and *Y* induces a chain map between the singular chain complexes of *X* and *Y*, and hence induces a map *f** between the singular homology of *X* and *Y* as well.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] When *X* and *Y* are both equal to the *n*-sphere, the map induced on homology defines the degree of the map *f*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The concept of chain map reduces to the one of boundary through the construction of the cone of a chain map.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] A chain homotopy offers a way to relate two chain maps that induce the same map on homology groups, even though the maps may be different.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Given two chain complexes *A* and *B*, and two chain maps *f*, *g* : *A* → *B*, a **chain homotopy** is a sequence of homomorphisms *h**n* : *A**n* → *B**n*+1 such that *hd**A* + *d**B**h* = *f* − *g*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The maps may be written out in a diagram as follows, but this diagram is not commutative.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The map *hd**A* + *d**B**h* is easily verified to induce the zero map on homology, for any *h*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] It immediately follows that *f* and *g* induce the same map on homology.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] One says *f* and *g* are **chain homotopic** (or simply **homotopic**), and this property defines an equivalence relation between chain maps.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] In the case of singular homology, a homotopy between continuous maps *f*, *g* : *X* → *Y* induces a chain homotopy between the chain maps corresponding to *f* and *g*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] This shows that two homotopic maps induce the same map on singular homology.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The name "chain homotopy" is motivated by this example.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] where the hat denotes the omission of a vertex.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] That is, the boundary of a singular simplex is the alternating sum of restrictions to its faces.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] It can be shown that ∂2 = 0, so $(C_{\bullet },\partial _{\bullet })$ is a chain complex; the **singular homology** $H_{\bullet }(X)$ is the homology of this complex.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Singular homology is a useful invariant of topological spaces up to homotopy equivalence.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The degree zero homology group is a free abelian group on the path-components of *X*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The differential *k*-forms on any smooth manifold *M* form a real vector space called Ω*k*(*M*) under addition.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The exterior derivative *d* maps Ω*k*(*M*) to Ω*k*+1(*M*), and *d*2 = 0 follows essentially from symmetry of second derivatives, so the vector spaces of *k*-forms along with the exterior derivative are a cochain complex.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The cohomology of this complex is called the **de Rham cohomology** of *M*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Locally constant functions are designated with its isomorphism $\Re ^{c}$ with c the count of mutually disconnected components of *M*.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] This way the complex was extended to leave the complex exact at zero-form level using the subset operator.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Smooth maps between manifolds induce chain maps, and smooth homotopies between maps induce chain homotopies.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] Chain complexes of K -modules with chain maps as morphisms form a category $\mathbf {Ch} _{K}$ , where K is a commutative ring.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] where a and b are any two homogeneous vectors in V and W respectively, and $\left|a\right|$ denotes the degree of a .
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] This tensor product makes the category $\mathbf {Ch} _{K}$ into a symmetric monoidal category.
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The identity object with respect to this monoidal product is the base ring K viewed as a chain complex in degree 0 .
[src:homological-algebra/chain-complex] The sign is necessary for the braiding to be a chain map.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] In mathematics, specifically category theory, certain functors may be *derived* to obtain other functors closely related to the original ones.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] This operation, while fairly abstract, unifies a number of constructions throughout mathematics.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] It was noted in various quite different settings that a short exact sequence often gives rise to a "long exact sequence".
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] **Derived functors** clarify and generalize many of these observations.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Suppose we are given a covariant left exact functor $F:\mathbf {A} \to \mathbf {B}$ between two abelian categories $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {B}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] and one could ask how to continue this sequence to the right to form a long exact sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Strictly speaking, this question is ill-posed, since there are always numerous different ways to continue a given exact sequence to the right.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] However, it turns out that if $\mathbf {A}$ is "nice enough", there is one canonical way of doing so, given by the right derived functors of F .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] From this we see that F is an exact functor if and only if $R^{1}F=0$ ; so in a sense the right derived functors of F measure "how far" F is from being exact.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] If the object A in the above short exact sequence is injective, then the sequence splits.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Applying any additive functor to a split sequence results in a split sequence, so in particular $R^{1}F(A)=0$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Right derived functors (for $i>0$ ) are zero on injectives: this is the motivation for the construction given below.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] The crucial assumption we need to make about our abelian category **A** is that it has *enough injectives*, meaning that for every object *A* in **A** there exists a monomorphism *A* → *I* where *I* is an injective object in **A**.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] The right derived functors of the covariant left-exact functor *F* : **A** → **B** are then defined as follows.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] where the *I* *i* are all injective (this is known as an *injective resolution* of *X*).
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Note: this is in general *not* an exact sequence anymore.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] But we can compute its cohomology at the *i*-th spot (the kernel of the map from *F*(*I**i*) modulo the image of the map to *F*(*I**i*)); we call the result *RiF*(*X*).
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Of course, various things have to be checked: the result does not depend on the given injective resolution of *X*, and any morphism *X* → *Y* naturally yields a morphism *RiF*(*X*) → *RiF*(*Y*), so that we indeed obtain a functor.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] (Technically, to produce well-defined derivatives of *F*, we would have to fix an injective resolution for every object of **A**.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] This choice of injective resolutions then yields functors *RiF*.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] The above-mentioned property of turning short exact sequences into long exact sequences is a consequence of the snake lemma.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] This tells us that the collection of derived functors is a δ-functor.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] If *X* is itself injective, then we can choose the injective resolution 0 → *X* → *X* → 0, and we obtain that *RiF*(*X*) = 0 for all *i* ≥ 1.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] In practice, this fact, together with the long exact sequence property, is often used to compute the values of right derived functors.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] An equivalent way to compute *RiF*(*X*) is the following: take an injective resolution of *X* as above, and let *K**i* be the image of the map *I**i*-1→*Ii* (for *i*=0, define *I**i*-1=0), which is the same as the kernel of *I**i*→*I**i*+1.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Let φ*i* : *I**i*-1→*K**i* be the corresponding surjective map.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] If one starts with a covariant *right-exact* functor G , and the category **A** has enough projectives (i.e. for every object A of **A** there exists an epimorphism $P\rightarrow A$ where P is a projective object), then one can define analogously the left-derived functors $L_{i}G$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] We apply G to this sequence, chop off the last term, and compute homology to get $L_{i}G(X)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Left derived functors are zero on all projective objects.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] One may also start with a *contravariant* left-exact functor F ; the resulting right-derived functors are then also contravariant.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] These right derived functors are zero on projectives and are therefore computed via projective resolutions.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] If X is a topological space, then the category $Sh(X)$ of all sheaves of abelian groups on X is an abelian category with enough injectives.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] The functor $\Gamma :Sh(X)\to Ab$ which assigns to each such sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ the group $\Gamma ({\mathcal {F}}):={\mathcal {F}}(X)$ of global sections is left exact, and the right derived functors are the sheaf cohomology functors, usually written as $H^{i}(X,{\mathcal {F}})$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Slightly more generally: if $(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ is a ringed space, then the category of all sheaves of ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ -modules is an abelian category with enough injectives, and we can again construct sheaf cohomology as the right derived functors of the global section functor.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] If R is a ring, then the category of all left R -modules is an abelian category with enough injectives.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] If A is a fixed left R -module, then the functor $\operatorname {Hom} (A,-):R{\text{-Mod}}\to {\mathfrak {Ab}}$ is left exact, and its right derived functors are the Ext functors $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{i}(A,-)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Alternatively $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{i}(-,B)$ can also be obtained as the left derived functor of the right exact functor $\operatorname {Hom} _{R}(-,B):R{\text{-Mod}}\to {\mathfrak {Ab}}^{op}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Various notions of cohomology are special cases of Ext functors and therefore also derived functors.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] The category of left R -modules also has enough projectives.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] If A is a fixed right R -module, then the tensor product with A gives a right exact covariant functor $A\otimes _{R}-:R{\text{-Mod}}\to Ab$ ; The category of modules has enough projectives so that left derived functors always exists.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] The left derived functors of the tensor functor are the Tor functors $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}^{R}(A,-)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Equivalently $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}^{R}(-,B)$ can be defined symmetrically as the left derived functors of $-\otimes B$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] In fact one can combine both definitions and define $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}^{R}(-,-)$ as the left derived of $-\otimes -:{\text{Mod-}}R\times R{\text{-Mod}}\to Ab$ .
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] This includes several notions of homology as special cases.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] This often mirrors the situation with Ext functors and cohomology.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Instead of taking individual left derived functors one can also take the total derived functor of the tensor functor.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] This gives rise to the derived tensor product $-\otimes ^{L}-:D({\text{Mod-}}R)\times D(R{\text{-Mod}})\to D(Ab)$ where D is the derived category.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Derived functors and the long exact sequences are "natural" in several technical senses.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Second, suppose η : *F* → *G* is a natural transformation from the left exact functor *F* to the left exact functor *G*.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Then natural transformations *Ri*η : *RiF* → *RiG* are induced, and indeed *Ri* becomes a functor from the functor category of all left exact functors from **A** to **B** to the full functor category of all functors from **A** to **B**.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Both of these naturalities follow from the naturality of the sequence provided by the snake lemma.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] The more modern (and more general) approach to derived functors uses the language of derived categories.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] In 1968 Quillen developed the theory of model categories, which give an abstract category-theoretic system of fibrations, cofibrations and weak equivalences.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Typically one is interested in the underlying homotopy category obtained by localizing against the weak equivalences.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] A Quillen adjunction is an adjunction between model categories that descends to an adjunction between the homotopy categories.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] For example, the category of topological spaces and the category of simplicial sets both admit Quillen model structures whose nerve and realization adjunction gives a Quillen adjunction that is in fact an equivalence of homotopy categories.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] Often we have a functor between two such model categories (e.g. the global sections functor sending a complex of Abelian sheaves to the obvious complex of Abelian groups) that preserves weak equivalences *within the subcategory of “good” (fibrant or cofibrant) objects*.
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] By first taking a fibrant or cofibrant resolution of an object and then applying that functor, we have successfully extended it to the whole category in such a way that weak equivalences are always preserved (and hence it descends to a functor from the homotopy category).
[src:homological-algebra/derived-functor] This is the “derived functor.” The “derived functors” of sheaf cohomology, for example, are the homologies of the output of this derived functor.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] In mathematics, an **exact sequence** is a sequence of morphisms between objects (for example, groups, rings, modules, and, more generally, objects of an abelian category) such that the image of one morphism equals the kernel of the next.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The sequence is called **exact** if it is exact at each $G_{i}$ for all $1\leq i<n$ , i.e., if the image of each homomorphism is equal to the kernel of the next.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The sequence of groups and homomorphisms may be either finite or infinite.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] A similar definition can be made for other algebraic structures.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] For example, one could have an exact sequence of vector spaces and linear maps, or of modules and module homomorphisms.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] More generally, the notion of an exact sequence makes sense in any category with kernels and cokernels, and more specially in abelian categories, where it is widely used.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] To understand the definition, it is helpful to consider relatively simple cases where the sequence is of group homomorphisms, is finite, and begins or ends with the trivial group.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Traditionally, this, along with the single identity element, is denoted 0 (additive notation, usually when the groups are abelian), or denoted 1 (multiplicative notation).
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Short exact sequences are exact sequences of the form $0\to A\xrightarrow {f} B\xrightarrow {g} C\to 0.$ As established above, for any such short exact sequence, f is a monomorphism and g is an epimorphism.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Furthermore, the image of f is equal to the kernel of g .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The short exact sequence $0\to A\xrightarrow {f} B\xrightarrow {g} C\to 0\,$ is called **split** if there exists a homomorphism $h:C\to B$ such that the composition $g\circ h$ is the identity map on C .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] A general exact sequence is sometimes called a **long exact sequence**, to distinguish from the special case of a short exact sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] where $K_{i}=\operatorname {im} (f_{i})$ for every i .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] By construction, the sequences *(2)* are exact at the $K_{i}$ 's (regardless of the exactness of *(1)*).
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Furthermore, *(1)* is a long exact sequence if and only if *(2)* are all short exact sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] See weaving lemma for details on how to re-form the long exact sequence from the short exact sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The first homomorphism maps each element i in the set of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ to the element $2i$ in $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The second homomorphism maps each element i in $\mathbb {Z}$ to an element j in the quotient group; that is, $j=i{\bmod {2}}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Here the hook arrow $\hookrightarrow$ indicates that the map $2\times$ from $\mathbb {Z}$ to $\mathbb {Z}$ is a monomorphism, and the two-headed arrow $\twoheadrightarrow$ indicates an epimorphism (the map ${\bmod {2}}$ ).
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] This is an exact sequence because the image $2\mathbb {Z}$ of the monomorphism is the kernel of the epimorphism.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] In this case the monomorphism is $2n\mapsto 2n$ and although it looks like an identity function, it is not onto (that is, not an epimorphism) because the odd numbers don't belong to $2\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The image of $2\mathbb {Z}$ through this monomorphism is however exactly the same subset of $\mathbb {Z}$ as the image of $\mathbb {Z}$ through $n\mapsto 2n$ used in the previous sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] This latter sequence does differ in the concrete nature of its first object from the previous one as $2\mathbb {Z}$ is not the same set as $\mathbb {Z}$ even though the two are isomorphic as groups.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Here 0 denotes the trivial group, the map from $\mathbb {Z}$ to $\mathbb {Z}$ is multiplication by 2, and the map from $\mathbb {Z}$ to the quotient group $\mathbb {Z} /2\mathbb {Z}$ is given by reducing integers modulo 2.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The first and third sequences are somewhat of a special case owing to the infinite nature of $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] It is not possible for a finite group to be mapped by inclusion (that is, by a monomorphism) as a proper subgroup of itself.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] $1\to N\to G\to G/N\to 1$ (here the trivial group is denoted $1,$ as these groups are not supposed to be abelian).
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] where $C_{n}$ is the cyclic group of order *n* and $D_{2n}$ is the dihedral group of order 2*n*, which is a non-abelian group.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The splitting lemma states that, for a short exact sequence $0\to A\;\xrightarrow {\ f\ } \;B\;\xrightarrow {\ g\ } \;C\to 0,$ the following conditions are equivalent.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] For non-commutative groups, the splitting lemma does not apply, and one has only the equivalence between the two last conditions, with "the direct sum" replaced with "a semidirect product".
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] In both cases, one says that such a short exact sequence *splits*.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The snake lemma shows how a commutative diagram with two exact rows gives rise to a longer exact sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The five lemma gives conditions under which the middle map in a commutative diagram with exact rows of length 5 is an isomorphism; the short five lemma is a special case thereof applying to short exact sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The importance of short exact sequences is underlined by the fact that every exact sequence results from "weaving together" several overlapping short exact sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The only portion of this diagram that depends on the cokernel condition is the object ${\textstyle C_{7}}$ and the final pair of morphisms ${\textstyle A_{6}\to C_{7}\to 0}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Conversely, given any list of overlapping short exact sequences, their middle terms form an exact sequence in the same manner.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] In the theory of abelian categories, short exact sequences are often used as a convenient language to talk about subobjects and factor objects.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] This problem is important in the classification of groups.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Notice that in an exact sequence, the composition $f_{i+1}\circ f_{i}$ maps $A_{i}$ to 0 in $A_{i+2}$ , so every exact sequence is a chain complex.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Furthermore, only $f_{i}$ -images of elements of $A_{i}$ are mapped to 0 by $f_{i+1}$ , so the homology of this chain complex is trivial.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Given any chain complex, its homology can therefore be thought of as a measure of the degree to which it fails to be exact.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] It comes up in algebraic topology in the study of relative homology; the Mayer–Vietoris sequence is another example.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Long exact sequences induced by short exact sequences are also characteristic of derived functors.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] Exact functors are functors that transform exact sequences into exact sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The sequence then yields the identities ${\text{curl}}\cdot {\text{grad}}=0$ and ${\text{div}}\cdot {\text{curl}}=0$ from advanced calculus.
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] A differential form $\omega \in \Omega ^{p}(X)$ is closed when $\omega \in {\text{im }}d^{p-1}$ , i.e. $\omega =d^{p-1}\omega '$ , and is consider exact when $\omega \in \ker d^{p}$ , that is, $d^{p}\omega =0$ .
[src:homological-algebra/exact-sequence] The de Rham complex is an exact sequence of modules if and only if every closed form is exact, which explains why the word exact is an adjective of "exact sequence".
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] In mathematics, the **Ext functors** are the derived functors of the Hom functor.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Along with the Tor functor, Ext is one of the core concepts of homological algebra, in which ideas from algebraic topology are used to define invariants of algebraic structures.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The cohomology of groups, Lie algebras, and associative algebras can all be defined in terms of Ext.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The name comes from the fact that the first Ext group Ext1 classifies extensions of one module by another.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] In the special case of abelian groups, Ext was introduced by Reinhold Baer in 1934.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] It was named by Samuel Eilenberg and Saunders MacLane in 1942, and applied to topology (the universal coefficient theorem for cohomology).
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] For modules over any ring, Ext was defined by Henri Cartan and Eilenberg in 1956.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Let R be a ring and let $R{\text{-Mod}}$ be the category of modules over R .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] (One can take this to mean either left R -modules or right R -modules.) For a fixed R -module A , let $T(B)={\text{Hom}}_{R}(A,B)$ for B in $R{\text{-Mod}}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] (Here ${\text{Hom}}_{R}(A,B)$ is the abelian group of R -linear maps from A to B ; this is an R -module if R is commutative.) This is a left exact functor from $R{\text{-Mod}}$ to the category of abelian groups $\mathbf {Ab}$ , and so it has right derived functors $R^{i}T$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] For each integer i , ${\text{Ext}}_{R}^{i}(A,B)$ is the cohomology of this complex at position i .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] An alternative definition uses the functor $G(A)=\operatorname {Hom} _{R}(A,B)$ , for a fixed R -module B .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] This is a contravariant functor, which can be viewed as a left exact functor from the opposite category $(R{\text{-Mod}})^{\text{op}}$ to $\mathbf {Ab}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Then $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{i}(A,B)$ is the cohomology of this complex at position i .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] One may wonder why the choice of resolution has been left vague so far.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] In fact, Cartan and Eilenberg showed that these constructions are independent of the choice of projective or injective resolution, and that both constructions yield the same Ext groups.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Moreover, for a fixed ring *R*, Ext is a functor in each variable (contravariant in *A*, covariant in *B*).
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] For a commutative ring *R* and *R*-modules *A* and *B*, Ext*i* *R*(*A*, *B*) is an *R*-module (using that Hom*R*(*A*, *B*) is an *R*-module in this case).
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] For a non-commutative ring *R*, Ext*i* *R*(*A*, *B*) is only an abelian group, in general.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] If *R* is an algebra over a ring *S* (which means in particular that *S* is commutative), then Ext*i* *R*(*A*, *B*) is at least an *S*-module.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Here are some of the basic properties and computations of $\operatorname {Ext}$ groups.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The $\operatorname {Ext}$ groups derive their name from their relation to extensions of modules.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Note that the Five lemma implies that the middle arrow is an isomorphism.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] There is a one-to-one correspondence between equivalence classes of extensions of A by B and elements of $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{1}(A,B)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Given $x\in \operatorname {Ext} (A,B)$ , choose $\beta \in \operatorname {Hom} (M,B)$ such that $\delta (\beta )=x$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Here, $X\to A$ is induced by the map $P\to A$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The bottom row is an extension of A by B , denoted $\xi$ , and the connecting map $\delta$ ensures that $\delta (\xi )=x$ , proving surjectivity.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] To show well-definedness on equivalence classes, suppose $\beta '$ is another lift of x .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Then there exists $f\in \operatorname {Hom} (P,B)$ such that $\beta '=\beta +f\circ j$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] If $X'$ is the pushout of j and $\beta '$ , then an isomorphism $X\cong X'$ is induced, making the extensions equivalent.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Here X is the pushout of j and $\gamma$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Thus, the set of equivalence classes of extensions of A by B is naturally isomorphic to $\operatorname {Ext} (A,B)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The trivial extension corresponds to the zero element of $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{1}(A,B)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The **Baer sum** is an explicit description of the abelian group structure on $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{1}(A,B)$ , viewed as the set of equivalence classes of extensions of A by B .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Up to equivalence of extensions, the Baer sum is commutative and has the trivial extension as identity element.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The negative of an extension $0\rightarrow B\rightarrow E\rightarrow A\rightarrow 0$ is the extension involving the same module E , but with the homomorphism $B\rightarrow E$ replaced by its negative.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Nobuo Yoneda defined the abelian groups Ext*n* **C**(*A*, *B*) for objects *A* and *B* in any abelian category **C**; this agrees with the definition in terms of resolutions if **C** has enough projectives or enough injectives.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Next, Ext1 **C**(*A*, *B*) is the set of equivalence classes of extensions of *A* by *B*, forming an abelian group under the Baer sum.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The Baer sum of two *n*-extensions as above is formed by letting $X''_{1}$ be the pullback of $X_{1}$ and $X'_{1}$ over *A*, and $X''_{n}$ be the pushout of $X_{n}$ and $X'_{n}$ under *B*.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] An important point is that Ext groups in an abelian category **C** can be viewed as sets of morphisms in a category associated to **C**, the derived category *D*(**C**).
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The objects of the derived category are complexes of objects in **C**.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] where an object of **C** is viewed as a complex concentrated in degree zero, and [*i*] means shifting a complex *i* steps to the left.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] which is simply the composition of morphisms in the derived category.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] The Yoneda product can also be described in more elementary terms.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] For *i* = *j* = 0, the product is the composition of maps in the category **C**.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] In general, the product can be defined by splicing together two Yoneda extensions.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Alternatively, the Yoneda product can be defined in terms of resolutions.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] (This is close to the definition of the derived category.) For example, let *R* be a ring, with *R*-modules *A*, *B*, *C*, and let *P*, *Q*, and *T* be projective resolutions of *A*, *B*, *C*.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Then Ext*i* *R*(*A*,*B*) can be identified with the group of chain homotopy classes of chain maps *P* → *Q*[*i*].
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] By any of these interpretations, the Yoneda product is associative.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] As a result, $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{*}(A,A)$ is a graded ring, for any *R*-module *A*.
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] For example, this gives the ring structure on group cohomology $H^{*}(G,\mathbb {Z} ),$ since this can be viewed as $\operatorname {Ext} _{\mathbb {Z} [G]}^{*}(\mathbb {Z} ,\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:homological-algebra/ext-functor] Also by associativity of the Yoneda product: for any *R*-modules *A* and *B*, $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{*}(A,B)$ is a module over $\operatorname {Ext} _{R}^{*}(A,A)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Homological algebra is the study of homological functors and the intricate algebraic structures that they entail; its development was closely intertwined with the emergence of category theory.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A central concept is that of chain complexes, which can be studied through their homology and cohomology.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Homological algebra affords the means to extract information contained in these complexes and present it in the form of homological invariants of rings, modules, topological spaces, and other "tangible" mathematical objects.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A spectral sequence is a powerful tool for this.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] It has played an enormous role in algebraic topology.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Its influence has gradually expanded and presently includes commutative algebra, algebraic geometry, algebraic number theory, representation theory, mathematical physics, operator algebras, complex analysis, and the theory of partial differential equations.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] *K*-theory is an independent discipline which draws upon methods of homological algebra, as does the noncommutative geometry of Alain Connes.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Homological algebra began to be studied in its most basic form in the late 19th century as a branch of topology and in the 1940s became an independent subject with the study of objects such as the ext functor and the tor functor, among others.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The notion of chain complex is central in homological algebra.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The elements of *C**n* are called *n*-**chains** and the homomorphisms *d**n* are called the **boundary maps** or **differentials**.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The **chain groups** *C**n* may be endowed with extra structure; for example, they may be vector spaces or modules over a fixed ring *R*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The differentials must preserve the extra structure if it exists; for example, they must be linear maps or homomorphisms of *R*-modules.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] For notational convenience, restrict attention to abelian groups (more correctly, to the category **Ab** of abelian groups); a celebrated theorem by Barry Mitchell implies the results will generalize to any abelian category.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Every chain complex defines two further sequences of abelian groups, the **cycles** *Z**n* = Ker *d**n* and the **boundaries** *B**n* = Im *d**n*+1, where Ker *d* and Im *d* denote the kernel and the image of *d*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A chain complex is called **acyclic** or an **exact sequence** if all its homology groups are zero.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Chain complexes arise in abundance in algebra and algebraic topology.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] In all these cases, there are natural differentials *d**n* making *C**n* into a chain complex, whose homology reflects the structure of the topological space *X*, the simplicial complex *K*, or the abelian group *A*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] In the case of topological spaces, we arrive at the notion of singular homology, which plays a fundamental role in investigating the properties of such spaces, for example, manifolds.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] On a technical level, homological algebra provides the tools for manipulating complexes and extracting this information.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Cohomology theories have been defined for many different objects such as topological spaces, sheaves, groups, rings, Lie algebras, and C*-algebras.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The study of modern algebraic geometry would be almost unthinkable without sheaf cohomology.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Central to homological algebra is the notion of exact sequence; these can be used to perform actual calculations.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A classical tool of homological algebra is that of derived functor; the most basic examples are functors Ext and Tor.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] With a diverse set of applications in mind, it was natural to try to put the whole subject on a uniform basis.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] There were several attempts before the subject settled down.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] These move from computability to generality.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The computational sledgehammer *par excellence* is the spectral sequence; these are essential in the Cartan-Eilenberg and Tohoku approaches where they are needed, for instance, to compute the derived functors of a composition of two functors.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Spectral sequences are less essential in the derived category approach, but still play a role whenever concrete computations are necessary.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] There have been attempts at 'non-commutative' theories which extend first cohomology as *torsors* (important in Galois cohomology).
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Note that the sequence of groups and homomorphisms may be either finite or infinite.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A similar definition can be made for certain other algebraic structures.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] More generally, the notion of an exact sequence makes sense in any category with kernels and cokernels.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The most common type of exact sequence is the **short exact sequence**.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] where ƒ is a monomorphism and *g* is an epimorphism.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] where 0 represents the zero object, such as the trivial group or a zero-dimensional vector space.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The placement of the 0's forces ƒ to be a monomorphism and *g* to be an epimorphism (see below).
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A long exact sequence is an exact sequence indexed by the natural numbers.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Consider the following commutative diagram in any abelian category (such as the category of abelian groups or the category of vector spaces over a given field) or in the category of groups.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The five lemma states that, if the rows are exact, *m* and *p* are isomorphisms, *l* is an epimorphism, and *q* is a monomorphism, then *n* is also an isomorphism.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] where the rows are exact sequences and 0 is the zero object.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Furthermore, if the morphism *f* is a monomorphism, then so is the morphism ker *a* → ker *b*, and if *g'* is an epimorphism, then so is coker *b* → coker *c*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The motivating prototype example of an abelian category is the category of abelian groups, **Ab**.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The theory originated in a tentative attempt to unify several cohomology theories by Alexander Grothendieck.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Abelian categories are very *stable* categories, for example they are regular and they satisfy the snake lemma.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Abelian categories are named after Niels Henrik Abel.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Suppose we are given a covariant left exact functor *F* : **A** → **B** between two abelian categories **A** and **B**.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] If 0 → *A* → *B* → *C* → 0 is a short exact sequence in **A**, then applying *F* yields the exact sequence 0 → *F*(*A*) → *F*(*B*) → *F*(*C*) and one could ask how to continue this sequence to the right to form a long exact sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] But it turns out that (if **A** is "nice" enough) there is one canonical way of doing so, given by the right derived functors of *F*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] From this we see that *F* is an exact functor if and only if *R*1*F* = 0; so in a sense the right derived functors of *F* measure "how far" *F* is from being exact.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Let *R* be a ring and let Mod*R* be the category of modules over *R*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] This is a left exact functor and thus has right derived functors *RnT*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Then (*RnT*)(*B*) is the cohomology of this complex.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Note that Hom*R*(*A,B*) is excluded from the complex.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] An alternative definition is given using the functor *G*(*A*)=Hom*R*(*A,B*).
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Then (*RnG*)(*A*) is the cohomology of this complex.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Again note that Hom*R*(*A,B*) is excluded.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] These two constructions turn out to yield isomorphic results, and so both may be used to calculate the Ext functor.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Suppose *R* is a ring, and denoted by *R*-**Mod** the category of left *R*-modules and by **Mod**-*R* the category of right *R*-modules (if *R* is commutative, the two categories coincide).
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Then *T* is a right exact functor from **Mod**-*R* to the category of abelian groups **Ab** (in the case when *R* is commutative, it is a right exact functor from **Mod**-*R* to **Mod**-*R*) and its left derived functors *LnT* are defined.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] (note that *A*⊗*R**B* does not appear and the last arrow is just the zero map) and take the homology of this complex.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Fix an abelian category, such as a category of modules over a ring.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Isomorphisms of *Er+1* with *H*(*Er*), the homology of *Er* with respect to *dr*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A doubly graded spectral sequence has a tremendous amount of data to keep track of, but there is a common visualization technique which makes the structure of the spectral sequence clearer.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] We have three indices, *r*, *p*, and *q*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] For each *r*, imagine that we have a sheet of graph paper.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] On this sheet, we will take *p* to be the horizontal direction and *q* to be the vertical direction.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] At each lattice point we have the object $E_{r}^{p,q}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] It is very common for *n* = *p* + *q* to be another natural index in the spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] *n* runs diagonally, northwest to southeast, across each sheet.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] In the homological case, the differentials have bidegree (−*r*, *r* − 1), so they decrease *n* by one.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] In the cohomological case, *n* is increased by one.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] When *r* is zero, the differential moves objects one space down or up.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] This is similar to the differential on a chain complex.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] When *r* is one, the differential moves objects one space to the left or right.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] When *r* is two, the differential moves objects just like a knight's move in chess.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] For higher *r*, the differential acts like a generalized knight's move.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A continuous map of topological spaces gives rise to a homomorphism between their *n*th homology groups for all *n*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] This basic fact of algebraic topology finds a natural explanation through certain properties of chain complexes.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Since it is very common to study several topological spaces simultaneously, in homological algebra one is led to simultaneous consideration of multiple chain complexes.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A **morphism** between two chain complexes, $F:C_{\bullet }\to D_{\bullet },$ is a family of homomorphisms of abelian groups $F_{n}:C_{n}\to D_{n}$ that commute with the differentials, in the sense that $F_{n-1}\circ d_{n}^{C}=d_{n}^{D}\circ F_{n}$ for all *n*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A morphism of chain complexes induces a morphism $H_{\bullet }(F)$ of their homology groups, consisting of the homomorphisms $H_{n}(F):H_{n}(C)\to H_{n}(D)$ for all *n*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] A morphism *F* is called a **quasi-isomorphism** if it induces an isomorphism on the *n*th homology for all *n*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] The following definition arises from a typical situation in algebra and topology.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] is a short exact sequence of abelian groups.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] By definition, this means that *f**n* is an injection, *g**n* is a surjection, and Im *f**n* = Ker *g**n*.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] where the homology groups of *L*, *M*, and *N* cyclically follow each other, and *δ**n* are certain homomorphisms determined by *f* and *g*, called the **connecting homomorphisms**.
[src:homological-algebra/homological-algebra] Topological manifestations of this theorem include the Mayer–Vietoris sequence and the long exact sequence for relative homology.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In homological algebra and algebraic topology, a **spectral sequence** is a means of computing homology groups by taking successive approximations.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Spectral sequences are a generalization of exact sequences, and since their introduction by Jean Leray (1946a, 1946b), they have become important computational tools, particularly in algebraic topology, algebraic geometry and homological algebra.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Motivated by problems in algebraic topology, Jean Leray introduced the notion of a sheaf and found himself faced with the problem of computing sheaf cohomology.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To compute sheaf cohomology, Leray introduced a computational technique now known as the Leray spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This gave a relation between cohomology groups of a sheaf and cohomology groups of the pushforward of the sheaf.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The relation involved an infinite process.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Leray found that the cohomology groups of the pushforward formed a natural chain complex, so that he could take the cohomology of the cohomology.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This was still not the cohomology of the original sheaf, but it was one step closer in a sense.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The cohomology of the cohomology again formed a chain complex, and its cohomology formed a chain complex, and so on.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The limit of this infinite process was essentially the same as the cohomology groups of the original sheaf.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] It was soon realized that Leray's computational technique was an example of a more general phenomenon.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Spectral sequences were found in diverse situations, and they gave intricate relationships among homology and cohomology groups coming from geometric situations such as fibrations and from algebraic situations involving derived functors.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] While their theoretical importance has decreased since the introduction of derived categories, they are still the most effective computational tool available.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This is true even when many of the terms of the spectral sequence are incalculable.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Unfortunately, because of the large amount of information carried in spectral sequences, they are difficult to grasp.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This information is usually contained in a rank three lattice of abelian groups or modules.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The easiest cases to deal with are those in which the spectral sequence eventually collapses, meaning that going out further in the sequence produces no new information.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Even when this does not happen, it is often possible to get useful information from a spectral sequence by various tricks.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Fix an abelian category, such as a category of modules over a ring, and a nonnegative integer $r_{0}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Usually the isomorphisms are suppressed and we write $E_{r+1}=H_{*}(E_{r},d_{r})$ instead.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] An object $E_{r}$ is called *sheet* (as in a sheet of paper), or sometimes a *page* or a *term*; an endomorphism $d_{r}$ is called *boundary map* or *differential*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Sometimes $E_{r+1}$ is called the *derived object* of $E_{r}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The notation used here is called *complementary degree*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Some authors write $E_{r}^{d,q}$ instead, where $d=p+q$ is the *total degree*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Depending upon the spectral sequence, the boundary map on the first sheet can have a degree which corresponds to *r* = 0, *r* = 1, or *r* = 2.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] For example, for the spectral sequence of a filtered complex, described below, *r*0 = 0, but for the Grothendieck spectral sequence, *r*0 = 2.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In the ungraded situation described above, *r*0 is irrelevant.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Mostly the objects we are talking about are chain complexes, that occur with descending (like above) or ascending order.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The most elementary example in the ungraded situation is a chain complex *C*•.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] An object *C*• in an abelian category of chain complexes naturally comes with a differential *d*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This forces *E*1 to be the complex *H*(*C*•): At the *i*′th location this is the *i*′th homology group of *C*•.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The only natural differential on this new complex is the zero map, so we let *d*1 = 0.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This forces $E_{2}$ to equal $E_{1}$ , and again our only natural differential is the zero map.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The terms of this spectral sequence stabilize at the first sheet because its only nontrivial differential was on the zeroth sheet.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Consequently, we can get no more information at later steps.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Usually, to get useful information from later sheets, we need extra structure on the $E_{r}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] An object $E_{r}$ can be seen as the rth checkered page of a book.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] On these sheets, we will take *p* to be the horizontal direction and *q* to be the vertical direction.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Now turning to the next page means taking homology, that is the $(r+1)$ th page is a subquotient of the rth page.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The total degree *n* = *p* + *q* runs diagonally, northwest to southeast, across each sheet.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The differentials change their direction with each turn with respect to r.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The red arrows demonstrate the case of a first quadrant sequence (see example below), where only the objects of the first quadrant are non-zero.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] While turning pages, either the domain or the codomain of all the differentials become zero.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] A cup product gives a ring structure to a cohomology group, turning it into a cohomology ring.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Thus, it is natural to consider a spectral sequence with a ring structure as well.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Let $E_{r}^{p,q}$ be a spectral sequence of cohomological type.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We say it has multiplicative structure if (i) $E_{r}$ are (doubly graded) differential graded algebras and (ii) the multiplication on $E_{r+1}$ is induced by that on $E_{r}$ via passage to cohomology.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] A typical example is the cohomological Serre spectral sequence for a fibration $F\to E\to B$ , when the coefficient group is a ring *R*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] It has the multiplicative structure induced by the cup products of fibre and base on the $E_{2}$ -page.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] However, in general the limiting term $E_{\infty }$ is not isomorphic as a graded algebra to H(*E*; *R*).
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The multiplicative structure can be very useful for calculating differentials on the sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Spectral sequences can be constructed by various ways.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In algebraic topology, an exact couple is perhaps the most common tool for the construction.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In algebraic geometry, spectral sequences are usually constructed from filtrations of cochain complexes.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Another technique for constructing spectral sequences is William Massey's method of exact couples.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Exact couples are particularly common in algebraic topology.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Despite this they are unpopular in abstract algebra, where most spectral sequences come from filtered complexes.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To define exact couples, we begin again with an abelian category.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] As before, in practice this is usually the category of doubly graded modules over a ring.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Exact couples are usually depicted as triangles.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We will see that *C* corresponds to the *E*0 term of the spectral sequence and that *A* is some auxiliary data.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To pass to the next sheet of the spectral sequence, we will form the **derived couple**.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] From here it is straightforward to check that (*A'*, *C'*, *f '*, *g'*, *h'*) is an exact couple.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] *C'* corresponds to the *E1* term of the spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In order to construct a spectral sequence, let *En* be *C*(*n*) and *dn* be *g*(*n*) o *h*(*n*).
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] A very common type of spectral sequence comes from a filtered cochain complex, as it naturally induces a bigraded object.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We require that the boundary map is compatible with the filtration, i.e. ${\textstyle d(F^{p}C^{n})\subset F^{p}C^{n+1}}$ , and that the filtration is *exhaustive*, that is, the union of the set of all ${\textstyle F^{p}C^{\bullet }}$ is the entire chain complex ${\textstyle C^{\bullet }}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Later, we will also assume that the filtration is *Hausdorff* or *separated*, that is, the intersection of the set of all ${\textstyle F^{p}C^{\bullet }}$ is zero.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The filtration is useful because it gives a measure of nearness to zero: As *p* increases, ${\textstyle F^{p}C^{\bullet }}$ gets closer and closer to zero.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We will construct a spectral sequence from this filtration where coboundaries and cocycles in later sheets get closer and closer to coboundaries and cocycles in the original complex.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This spectral sequence is doubly graded by the filtration degree *p* and the complementary degree *q* = *n* − *p*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] $C^{\bullet }$ has only a single grading and a filtration, so we first construct a doubly graded object for the first page of the spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To get the second grading, we will take the associated graded object with respect to the filtration.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Since we assumed that the boundary map was compatible with the filtration, $E_{0}$ is a doubly graded object and there is a natural doubly graded boundary map $d_{0}$ on $E_{0}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To get $E_{1}$ , we take the homology of $E_{0}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] $Z_{1}^{p,q}$ are exactly the elements which the differential pushes up one level in the filtration, and $B_{1}^{p,q}$ are exactly the image of the elements which the differential pushes up zero levels in the filtration.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This suggests that we should choose $Z_{r}^{p,q}$ to be the elements which the differential pushes up *r* levels in the filtration and $B_{r}^{p,q}$ to be image of the elements which the differential pushes up *r-1* levels in the filtration.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] For this to make sense, we must find a differential $d_{r}$ on each $E_{r}$ and verify that it leads to homology isomorphic to $E_{r+1}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] is defined by restricting the original differential d defined on $C^{p+q}$ to the subobject $Z_{r}^{p,q}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] It is straightforward to check that the homology of $E_{r}$ with respect to this differential is $E_{r+1}$ , so this gives a spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Unfortunately, the differential is not very explicit.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Determining differentials or finding ways to work around them is one of the main challenges to successfully applying a spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Another common spectral sequence is the spectral sequence of a double complex.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] A **double complex** is a collection of objects *Ci,j* for all integers *i* and *j* together with two differentials, dI and dII. dI is assumed to decrease *i*, and dII is assumed to decrease *j*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Furthermore, we assume that the differentials *anticommute*, so that *d*I *d*II + *d*II *d*I = 0.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We will do this by filtering our double complex in two different ways.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To get a spectral sequence, we will reduce to the previous example.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We define the *total complex* *T*(*C*•,•) to be the complex whose *n*′th term is $\bigoplus _{i+j=n}C_{i,j}$ and whose differential is dI + dII.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This is a complex because dI and dII are anticommuting differentials.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To show that these spectral sequences give information about the iterated homologies, we will work out the *E*0, *E*1, and *E*2 terms of the I filtration on *T*(*C*•,•).
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To find the *E*1 term, we need to determine dI + dII on *E*0.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Consequently, the differential on *E*0 is the map *C**p*,*q* → *C**p*,*q*−1 induced by dI + dII.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] But dI has the wrong degree to induce such a map, so dI must be zero on *E*0.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Because *E*1 was exactly the homology with respect to dII, dII is zero on *E*1.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] What remains is to find a relationship between these two spectral sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] It will turn out that as *r* increases, the two sequences will become similar enough to allow useful comparisons.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Let *E**r* be a spectral sequence, starting with say *r* = 1.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We say a spectral sequence **converges weakly** if there is a graded object $H^{\bullet }$ with a filtration $F^{\bullet }H^{n}$ for every n , and for every p there exists an isomorphism $E_{\infty }^{p,q}\cong F^{p}H^{p+q}/F^{p+1}H^{p+q}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The spectral sequence is **regular** or **degenerates at $r_{0}$**if the differentials $d_{r}^{p,q}$ are zero for all $r\geq r_{0}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] If in particular there is $r_{0}\geq 2$ , such that the $r_{0}^{th}$ sheet is concentrated on a single row or a single column, then we say it **collapses**.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] It is very common to write the $E_{2}^{p,q}$ term on the left-hand side of the abutment, because this is the most useful term of most spectral sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The spectral sequence of an unfiltered chain complex degenerates at the first sheet (see first example): since nothing happens after the zeroth sheet, the limiting sheet $E_{\infty }$ is the same as $E_{1}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The five-term exact sequence of a spectral sequence relates certain low-degree terms and *E*∞ terms.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] $E_{\infty }^{p,q}$ is a natural candidate for the abutment of this spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Convergence is not automatic, but happens in many cases.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In particular, if the filtration is finite and consists of exactly *r* nontrivial steps, then the spectral sequence degenerates after the *r*th sheet.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Convergence also occurs if the complex and the filtration are both bounded below or both bounded above.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To see what this implies for $Z_{\infty }^{p,q}$ recall that we assumed that the filtration was separated.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This implies that as *r* increases, the kernels shrink, until we are left with $Z_{\infty }^{p,q}=\ker(F^{p}C^{p+q}\rightarrow C^{p+q+1})$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] For $B_{\infty }^{p,q}$ , recall that we assumed that the filtration was exhaustive.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This implies that as *r* increases, the images grow until we reach $B_{\infty }^{p,q}={\text{im }}(C^{p+q-1}\rightarrow C^{p+q})\cap F^{p}C^{p+q}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] that is, the abutment of the spectral sequence is the *p*th graded part of the *(p+q)*th homology of *C*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Using the spectral sequence of a filtered complex, we can derive the existence of long exact sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Choose a short exact sequence of cochain complexes 0 → *A*• → *B*• → *C*• → 0, and call the first map *f*• : *A*• → *B*•.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We get natural maps of homology objects *Hn*(*A*•) → *Hn*(*B*•) → *Hn*(*C*•), and we know that this is exact in the middle.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] It remains to show that this sequence is exact at the *A* and *C* spots.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Notice that this spectral sequence degenerates at the *E*2 term because the differentials have bidegree (2, −1).
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] But we also have a direct description of the *E*2 term as the homology of the *E*1 term.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The former gives exactness at the *C* spot, and the latter gives exactness at the *A* spot.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In general, *the two gradings on ⁠ $H^{p+q}(T(C_{\bullet ,\bullet }))$ ⁠ are distinct*.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Despite this, it is still possible to gain useful information from these two spectral sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Let *R* be a ring, let *M* be a right *R*-module and *N* a left *R*-module.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Recall that the derived functors of the tensor product are denoted Tor.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Tor is defined using a projective resolution of its first argument.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] However, it turns out that $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}(M,N)=\operatorname {Tor} _{i}(N,M)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] While this can be verified without a spectral sequence, it is very easy with spectral sequences.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Choose projective resolutions $P_{\bullet }$ and $Q_{\bullet }$ of *M* and *N*, respectively.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Consider these as complexes which vanish in negative degree having differentials *d* and *e*, respectively.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] We can construct a double complex whose terms are $C_{i,j}=P_{i}\otimes Q_{j}$ and whose differentials are $d\otimes 1$ and $(-1)^{\textrm {I}}(1\otimes e)$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Since the two complexes are resolutions, their homology vanishes outside of degree zero.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In particular, the $E_{p,q}^{2}$ terms vanish except along the lines *q* = 0 (for the I spectral sequence) and *p* = 0 (for the II spectral sequence).
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Finally, when *p* and *q* are equal, the two right-hand sides are equal, and the commutativity of Tor follows.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Consider a spectral sequence where $E_{r}^{p,q}$ vanishes for all p less than some $p_{0}$ and for all q less than some $q_{0}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] If $p_{0}$ and $q_{0}$ can be chosen to be zero, this is called a **first-quadrant spectral sequence**.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] To see this, note that either the domain or the codomain of the differential is zero for the considered cases.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] In visual terms, the sheets stabilize in a growing rectangle (see picture above).
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The spectral sequence need not degenerate, however, because the differential maps might not all be zero at once.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Similarly, the spectral sequence also converges if $E_{r}^{p,q}$ vanishes for all p greater than some $p_{0}$ and for all q greater than some $q_{0}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Let $E_{p,q}^{r}$ be a homological spectral sequence such that $E_{p,q}^{2}=0$ for all *p* other than 0, 1.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] hence the spectral sequence degenerates: $E^{\infty }=E^{2}$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Next, let $E_{p,q}^{r}$ be a spectral sequence whose second page consists only of two lines *q* = 0, 1.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] This need not degenerate at the second page but it still degenerates at the third page as the differentials there have degree (-3, 2).
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Now, say, the spectral sequence converges to *H* with a filtration *F* as in the previous example.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] The computation in the previous section generalizes in a straightforward way.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] the spectral sequence converges on $E^{n+1}=E^{\infty }$ .
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] With an obvious notational change, the type of the computations in the previous examples can also be carried out for cohomological spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Let $E_{p,q}^{r}$ be a spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] For a spectral sequence $E_{r}^{p,q}$ of cohomological type, the analogous statements hold.
[src:homological-algebra/spectral-sequence] Determining these maps are fundamental for computing many differentials in the Serre spectral sequence.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] In mathematics, the **Tor functors** are the derived functors of the tensor product of modules over a ring.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] Along with the Ext functor, Tor is one of the central concepts of homological algebra, in which ideas from algebraic topology are used to construct invariants of algebraic structures.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] The homology of groups, Lie algebras, and associative algebras can all be defined in terms of Tor.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] The name comes from a relation between the first Tor group Tor1 and the torsion subgroup of an abelian group.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] In the special case of abelian groups, Tor was introduced by Eduard Čech in 1935 and named by Samuel Eilenberg around 1950.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] It was first applied to the Künneth theorem and universal coefficient theorem in topology.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] Write $R{\textsf {-Mod}}$ for the category of left R -modules and ${\textsf {Mod-}}R$ for the category of right R -modules.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] (If R is commutative, the two categories can be identified.) For a fixed left R -module B , let $T(A)=A\otimes _{R}B$ for A in ${\textsf {Mod-}}R$ .
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] This is a right exact functor from ${\textsf {Mod-}}R$ to the category of abelian groups ${\textbf {Ab}}$ , and so it has left derived functors ${\mathcal {L}}_{i}T$ .
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] The Tor groups are the abelian groups defined by $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}^{R}(A,B)=({\mathcal {L}}_{i}T)(A),$ for an integer i .
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] For each integer i , the group $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}^{R}(A,B)$ is the homology of this complex at position i .
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] Moreover, $\operatorname {Tor} _{0}^{R}(A,B)$ is the cokernel of the map $P_{1}\otimes _{R}B\to P_{0}\otimes _{R}B$ , which is isomorphic to $A\otimes _{R}B$ .
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] Alternatively, one can define $\mathrm {Tor}$ by fixing A and taking the left derived functors of the right exact functor $G(B)=A\otimes _{R}B$ .
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] That is, tensor A with a projective resolution of B and take homology.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] Cartan and Eilenberg showed that these constructions are independent of the choice of projective resolution, and that both constructions yield the same Tor groups.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] Moreover, for a fixed ring R , $\mathrm {Tor}$ is a functor in each variable (from R -modules to abelian groups).
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] For a commutative ring R and R -modules A and B , $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}^{R}(A,B)$ is an R -module (using that $A\otimes _{R}B$ is an R -module in this case).
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] For a non-commutative ring R , $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}^{R}(A,B)$ is only an abelian group, in general.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] If R is an algebra over a ring S (which means in particular that S is commutative), then $\operatorname {Tor} _{i}^{R}(A,B)$ is at least an S -module.
[src:homological-algebra/tor-functor] Here are some of the basic properties and computations of Tor groups.
